    "summary": "The deposition of Romulus Augustulus by Odoacer (476 AD) is conventionally dated as the [[event:85|fall of the Western Roman Empire]] — the moment when the last emperor claiming to rule the western half of the Roman world was overthrown by a Germanic chieftain who declined to appoint a successor, instead sending the imperial regalia to the Eastern Emperor in Constantinople with a message that one emperor sufficed for the whole empire. Romulus Augustulus (his name combining Rome's legendary founder with the diminutive '-ulus,' suggesting his contemporaries viewed him as a 'little Augustus') was actually a usurper of dubious legitimacy, installed by his father Orestes; the Eastern Empire never recognized him.\n\nOdoacer was a Germanic military commander (of mixed Scirian/Hunnic heritage) who led the mercenary troops of the Western Roman army in a mutiny demanding land grants, defeated Orestes, and captured Ravenna. He ruled Italy for seventeen years as king — maintaining Roman administrative structures, Latin law, and the Senate — until [[event:2040|Theoderic the Ostrogoth]] invaded at Constantinople's instigation in 489 AD and killed Odoacer in 493 AD. The 'fall' of 476 AD was recognized as significant mainly in hindsight; contemporaries saw it as one more coup in a long series. The Eastern Roman Empire (Byzantine Empire) continued for another 977 years, and modern historians debate whether 476 is the most meaningful date for the 'end' of Rome.",
